obj_root_law_sections_4_content:
  string
  line 4
  line `THE ACTUARIES ACT, 2006`
  line `A CT N O. 35 OF 2006`
  line `[27 th August, 2006.]`
  line `An Act to provide for regulating and developing the profession of Actuaries and for matters`
  line `connected therewith or incidental thereto.`
  line `B E it enacted by Parliament in the Fifty-seventh Year of the Republic of India as follows: —`
  line `CHAPTER I`
  line `P RELIMINARY`
  line `1. Short title, extent and commencement. — ( 1 ) This Act may be called the Actuaries Act, 2006.`
  line `( 2 ) It extends to the whole of India.`
  line `( 3 ) It shall come into force on such date 1 as the Central Government may, by notification in the`
  line `Official Gazette, appoint:`
  line `Provided that different dates may be appointed for different provisions of this Act and any reference`
  line `in any such provision to the commencement of this Act shall be construed as a reference to the`
  line `commencement of that provision.`
  line `2. Definitions. — ( 1 ) In this Act, unless the context otherwise requires, —`
  line `( a ) "Actuary" means a person skilled in determining the present effects of future contingent`
  line `events or in finance modelling and risk analysis in different areas of insurance, or calculating the`
  line `value of life interests and insurance risks, or designing and pricing of policies, working out the`
  line `benefits, recommending rates relating to insurance business, annuities, insurance and pension rates on`
  line `the basis of empirically based tables and includes a statistician engaged in such technology, taxation,`
  line `employees' benefits and such other risk management and investments and who is a fellow member of`
  line `the Institute; and the expression "actuarial science" shall be construed accordingly;`
  line `( b ) "Actuarial Society" means the Actuarial Society of India registered under the Societies`
  line `Registration Act, 1860 (21 of 1860) and the Bombay Public Trusts Act, 1950 (Bombay Act No`
  line `XXXIX of 1950);`
  line `( c ) "appointed day" means the date on which the Institute is constituted under sub-section ( 1 ) of`
  line `section 3;`
  line `( d ) "Authority" means the Appellate Authority referred to in section 32;`
  line `( e ) "Board" means the Quality Review Board constituted under sub-section ( 1 ) of section 43;`
  line `( f ) "Council" means the Council of the Institute as referred to in section 12;`
  line `( g ) "fellow" means a fellow member of the Institute;`
  line `( h ) "Institute" means the Institute of Actuaries of India constituted under section 3;`
  line `( i ) "member" means an individual whose name appears in the register of members maintained by`
  line `the Institute;`
  line `( j ) "prescribed" means prescribed by rules made under this Act;`
  line `( k ) "President" means the President of the Council;`
  line `( l ) "register" means the register of members maintained by the Institute under this Act;`
  line `( m ) "specified" means specified by regulations made under this Act;`
  line `1. 10th November, 2006, vide notification No. S.O. 1912(E) dated 28th November, 2006, see Gazette of India, Extraordinary,`
  line `Part II, sec. 3( ii )`
obj_root_law_sections_4_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_5:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-5
  sectionNo (5)
  orderNo 5
  title `Page 5`
  content obj_root_law_sections_5_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_5_footnotes
  sourcePage 5
obj_root_law_sections_5_content:
  string
  line 5
  line `( n ) "Tribunal" means a Tribunal established under sub-section ( 1 ) of section 16;`
  line `( o ) ''Vice-President'' means the Vice-President of the Council;`
  line `( p ) "year" means the period commencing on the 1st day of April of any year and ending on the`
  line `31st day of March of the succeeding year.`
  line `( 2 ) Save as otherwise provided in this Act, a member of the Institute shall be deemed "to be in`
  line `practice" when individually or in partnership with Actuaries in practice as a member or an employee of a`
  line `company, he, whether or not in consideration of remuneration received or to be received, —`
  line `( i ) engages himself in actuarial profession; or`
  line `( ii ) offers to perform or performs services involving the application of actuarial techniques in the`
  line `fields of insurance, pension, investment, finance and management; or`
  line `( iii ) renders such other services as, in the opinion of the Council, are or may be rendered by an`
  line `actuary in practice; or`
  line `( iv ) is in employment of a person engaged in one or more of the activities mentioned in clauses`
  line `( i ), ( ii ) and ( iii ) above,`
  line `and the words "to be in practice" with their grammatical variations and cognate expressions shall be`
  line `construed accordingly.`
  line `Explanation. — For the purposes of this sub-section, the expression "company" includes a public`
  line `financial institution as defined in section 4A of the Companies Act, 1956 (1 of 1956).`
  line `CHAPTER II`
  line `I NSTITUTE OF A CTUARIES OF I NDIA`
  line `3. Incorporation of Institute. — ( 1 ) With effect from such date as the Central Government may, by`
  line `notification in the Official Gazette, appoint, all persons whose names are entered in the register of the`
  line `Actuarial Society at the commencement of this Act and all persons who may thereafter have their names`
  line `entered in the register to be maintained under this Act, so long as they continue to have their names borne`
  line `on the register, are hereby constituted a body corporate by the name of the Institute of Actuaries of India`
  line `and all such persons shall be known as members of the Institute.`
  line `( 2 ) The Institute shall have perpetual succession and a common seal and shall have power to acquire,`
  line `hold and dispose of property, both movable and immovable, and shall by its name sue or be sued.`
  line `( 3 ) The head office of the Institute shall be situated at such place as may be decided by the Central`
  line Government.
  line `4. Transfer of assets, liabilities, etc., of Actuarial Society. — On the appointed day, —`
  line `( a ) all the assets and liabilities of the Actuarial Society shall stand transferred to, and vested in,`
  line `the Institute.`
  line `Explanation. — The assets of the Actuarial Society shall be deemed to include all rights and`
  line `powers and all properties, whether movable or immovable, including, in particular, cash balances,`
  line `deposits and all other interests and rights in, or arising out of, such properties as may be in the`
  line `possession of the said Society and all books of account and other documents relating to the same; and`
  line `liabilities shall be deemed to include all debts, liabilities and obligations of whatever kind;`
  line `( b ) without prejudice to the provisions of clause ( a ), all debts, obligations and liabilities incurred,`
  line `all contracts entered into and all matters and things engaged to be done by, with or for the Actuarial`
  line `Society immediately before that day, for or in connection with the purpose of the said Society, shall`
  line `be deemed to have been incurred, entered into or engaged to be done by, with or for, the Institute;`
  line `( c ) all sums of money due to the Actuarial Society immediately before that day shall be deemed`
  line `to be due to the Institute; and`
obj_root_law_sections_5_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_6:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-6
  sectionNo (6)
  orderNo 6
  title `Page 6`
  content obj_root_law_sections_6_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_6_footnotes
  sourcePage 6
obj_root_law_sections_6_content:
  string
  line 6
  line `( d ) all suits and other legal proceedings instituted or which could have been instituted by or`
  line `against the Actuarial Society immediately before that day may be continued or may be instituted by`
  line `or against the Institute.`
  line `5. Objects of Institute. — The objects of the Institute shall be —`
  line `( a ) to promote, uphold and develop the standards of professional education, training, knowledge,`
  line `practice and conduct amongst Actuaries;`
  line `( b ) to promote the status of the Actuarial profession;`
  line `( c ) to regulate the practice by the members of the profession of Actuary;`
  line `( d ) to promote, in the public interest, knowledge and research in all matters relevant to Actuarial`
  line `science and its application; and`
  line `( e ) to do all such other things as may be incidental or conducive to the above objects or any of`
  line them.
  line `6. Entry of names in register. — ( 1 ) Any of the following persons shall be entitled to have his name`
  line `entered in the register, namely: —`
  line `( a ) any person who immediately before the appointed day was an associate or a fellow (including`
  line `an honorary fellow) of the Actuarial Society;`
  line `( b ) any person who has passed the examination conducted by the Actuarial Society and has`
  line `completed training either as specified by the said Society or as specified by the Council, except any`
  line `such person who is not a permanent resident of India;`
  line `( c ) any person who has passed such examination and completed such training, as may be`
  line `specified for membership of the Institute;`
  line `( d ) any person who has passed such other examination and completed such other training outside`
  line `India as is specified as being equivalent to the examination and training specified under this Act for`
  line `membership of the Institute:`
  line `Provided that in the case of any person belonging to any of the classes mentioned in this sub-section`
  line `who is not permanently residing in India, the Central Government or the Council may impose such further`
  line `conditions as it may deem necessary or expedient in the public interest.`
  line `( 2 ) Every person mentioned in clause ( a ) of sub-section ( 1 ) may have his name entered in the register`
  line `without the payment of any entrance fee.`
  line `( 3 ) Every person belonging to any of the classes mentioned in clauses ( b ), ( c ) and ( d ) of sub-section`
  line `( 1 ) shall have his name entered in the register on an application being made and granted in the specified`
  line `manner and on payment of such fees, as may be specified.`
  line `( 4 ) The Council shall take such steps as may be necessary for the purpose of having the names of all`
  line `persons belonging to the class mentioned in clause ( a ) of sub-section ( 1 ) entered in the register before the`
  line `appointed day.`
  line `( 5 ) Notwithstanding anything contained in this section, the Council may confer on any person`
  line `honorary fellow membership, if the Council is of the opinion that such person has made a significant`
  line `contribution to the profession of Actuary and thereupon the Council shall enter the name of such person`
  line `in the register but such person shall not have any voting rights in any election or meetings of the Institute`
  line `and shall not also be required to pay any fee to the Institute.`
  line `7. Associates and fellows. — ( 1 ) The members of the Institute shall be divided into two classes`
  line `designated respectively as associates and fellows.`
  line `( 2 ) Any person other than a person to whom the provisions of sub-section ( 3 ) apply, shall, on his`
  line `name being entered in the register, be deemed to have become an associate and as long as his name`
  line `remains so entered, shall be entitled to use the letters "AIAI" after his name to indicate that he is an`
  line associate.
obj_root_law_sections_6_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_7:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-7
  sectionNo (7)
  orderNo 7
  title `Page 7`
  content obj_root_law_sections_7_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_7_footnotes
  sourcePage 7
obj_root_law_sections_7_content:
  string
  line 7
  line `( 3 ) Any person who was a fellow of the Actuarial Society and who is entitled to have his name`
  line `entered in the register under clause ( a ) of sub-section ( 1 ) of section 6 shall be entered in the register as a`
  line fellow.
  line `( 4 ) Any person whose name is entered in the register as fellow shall, so long as his name remains so`
  line `entered, be entitled to use the letters "FIAI" after his name to indicate that he is a fellow.`
  line `8. Honorary, affiliate and student members. — ( 1 ) The Council may choose, in such manner as may`
  line `be specified, any person of eminence in matters relating to and of interest to the profession of Actuary as`
  line `an honorary member of the Institute provided that he is not practicing as an Actuary.`
  line `( 2 ) Any person, who is a fellow member, or is a holder of membership considered equivalent to the`
  line `fellow membership of the Institute, of any other institution similar to the Institute, whether within or`
  line `outside India, may be admitted as an affiliate member for such period, and on such terms and conditions`
  line `as may be specified.`
  line `( 3 ) Any person who enrolls himself for examination of the Institute, and possesses such academic`
  line `qualifications as may be specified, may be admitted as a student member of the Institute on such terms`
  line `and conditions as may be specified.`
  line `( 4 ) An honorary member or an affiliate member or a student member shall have no right to vote on`
  line `any matter or resolution in any meeting of the Institute.`
  line `9. Certificate of practice. — ( 1 ) No member of the Institute shall be entitled to practice unless he`
  line `fulfils the qualifications as may be specified and obtains from the Council a certificate of practice.`
  line `( 2 ) A member who desires to be entitled to practice shall make an application in such form and pay`
  line `such annual fee for certificate of practice as may be specified and such fee shall be payable on or before`
  line `the first day of April in each year.`
  line `( 3 ) The certificate of practice obtained under sub-section ( 1 ) may be cancelled by the Council under`
  line `such circumstances as may be specified.`
  line `10. Members to be known as Actuaries. — Every member of the Institute in practice shall, and any`
  line `other member may, use the designation of an Actuary and no member using such designation shall use`
  line `any other description whether in addition thereto or in substitution therefor:`
  line `Provided that nothing contained in this section shall be deemed to prohibit any such member from`
  line `adding any other description or letters to his name, if entitled thereto, to indicate membership of such`
  line `other Institute, whether in India or elsewhere, as may be recognised in this behalf by the Council, or any`
  line `other qualification that he may possess, or to prohibit a firm, all the partners of which are members of the`
  line `Institute and in practice, from being known by its firm name as Actuaries.`
  line `11. Disqualifications. — Notwithstanding anything contained in section 6, a person shall not be`
  line `entitled to have his name entered in, or borne on, the register if he —`
  line `( a ) has not attained the age of twenty-one years at the time of his application for the entry of his`
  line `name in the register; or`
  line `( b ) is of unsound mind and stands so adjudged by a competent court; or`
  line `( c ) is an undischarged insolvent; or`
  line `( d ) being a discharged insolvent, has not obtained from the court a certificate stating that his`
  line `insolvency was caused by misfortune and without any misconduct on his part; or`
  line `( e ) has been convicted by a competent court whether within or outside India, of an offence`
  line `involving moral turpitude and punishable with imprisonment or of an offence, not of a technical`
  line `nature, committed by him in his professional capacity unless in respect of the offence committed he`
  line `has either been granted a pardon or, on an application made by him in this behalf, the Central`
  line `Government has, by an order in writing, removed the disqualification; or`
  line `( f ) has been removed from the membership of the Institute on being found on inquiry to have`
  line `been guilty of a professional or other misconduct:`
obj_root_law_sections_7_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_8:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-8
  sectionNo (8)
  orderNo 8
  title `Page 8`
  content obj_root_law_sections_8_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_8_footnotes
  sourcePage 8
obj_root_law_sections_8_content:
  string
  line 8
  line `Provided that a person who has been removed from the membership for a specified period shall not be`
  line `entitled to have his name entered in the Register until the expiry of such period.`
  line `12. Composition of Council of Institute. — ( 1 )There shall be a Council of the Institute for the`
  line `management of the affairs of the Institute and for discharging the functions assigned to it by or under this`
  line Act.
  line `( 2 ) The Council shall be composed of the following persons, namely: —`
  line `( a ) a minimum of nine and not more than twelve persons from amongst fellow members to be`
  line `elected by the fellow and the associate members of the Institute in such manner as may be prescribed:`
  line `Provided that a fellow of the Institute, who has been found guilty of any professional or other`
  line `misconduct and whose name is removed from the Register or has been awarded penalty of fine, shall`
  line `not be eligible to contest election, —`
  line `( i ) in case of misconduct falling under the Schedule of this Act [except Part IV( B )], for a`
  line `period of three years; or`
  line `( ii ) in case of misconduct falling under Part IV( B ) of the Schedule of this Act, for a period of`
  line `six years,`
  line `after the completion of the period of removal of name of the fellow from the Register or the payment`
  line `of fine is made, as the case may be; and`
  line `( b ) ( i ) an officer not below the rank of Joint Secretary to the Government of India, to be`
  line `nominated by the Central Government to represent the Ministry of Finance;`
  line `( ii ) one person from the Insurance Regulatory and Development Authority constituted under the`
  line `Insurance Regulatory and Development Authority Act, 1999 (41 of 1999) nominated by the Central`
  line `Government; and`
  line `( iii ) not more than two persons having knowledge in the field of life insurance, general insurance,`
  line `finance, economics, law, accountancy or any other discipline which in the opinion of the Central`
  line `Government, would be useful to the Council, to be nominated in such manner as may be prescribed:`
  line `Provided that till such time as the Council is constituted under this Act, the Executive Committee of`
  line `the Actuarial Society shall discharge all the functions and shall have all the powers of the Council.`
  line `( 3 ) No person holding a post under the Central Government or a State Government, as the case may`
  line `be, shall be eligible for election to the Council under clause ( a ) of sub-section ( 2 ).`
  line `( 4 ) One-third of the members of the Council referred to in clause ( a ) of sub-section ( 2 ) shall retire as`
  line `soon as may be on the expiration of every second year by rotation but shall be eligible for re-election.`
  line `( 5 ) Any person nominated under clause ( b ) of sub-section ( 2 ) shall hold office for a period of six`
  line `years from the date of his nomination unless he is removed earlier by the Central Government and shall`
  line `be eligible for re-nomination:`
  line `Provided that he shall be given an opportunity of being heard before such removal.`
  line `13. Annual general meetings. — The Council shall every year hold an annual general meeting of the`
  line `Institute to elect its members under clause ( a ) of sub-section ( 2 ) of section 12, or to discuss any matter`
  line `which it deems fit, and not more than fifteen months shall elapse between the date of one annual general`
  line `meeting of the Institute and that of the next:`
  line `Provided that from the appointed day the Institute may hold its first annual general meeting within a`
  line `period of not more than eighteen months and if such general meeting is held within that period, it shall`
  line `not be necessary for the Institute to hold any general meeting in that year:`
  line `Provided further that the Central Government may, for sufficient reasons, extend the time within`
  line `which any general meeting shall be held.`
obj_root_law_sections_8_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_9:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-9
  sectionNo (9)
  orderNo 9
  title `Page 9`
  content obj_root_law_sections_9_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_9_footnotes
  sourcePage 9
obj_root_law_sections_9_content:
  string
  line 9
  line `14. Re-election to Council. — ( 1 ) Subject to the provisions of sub-section ( 2 ), a member of the`
  line `Council elected under clause ( a ) of sub- section ( 2 ) of section 12 shall be eligible for re-election but not`
  line `for more than two consecutive terms.`
  line `( 2 ) A member of the Council, who is or has been elected, as the President under sub-section ( 1 ) of`
  line `section 17, shall not be eligible for election or nomination as a member of the Council.`
  line `15. Settlement of disputes regarding election. — In case of any dispute regarding any election under`
  line `clause ( a ) of sub-section ( 2 ) of section 12, the aggrieved person may make an application within thirty`
  line `days from the date of the declaration of the result of the election to the Council which shall forward the`
  line `same forthwith to the Central Government.`
  line `16. Establishment of Tribunal. — ( 1 ) On receipt of any application under section 15, the Central`
  line `Government shall, by notification, establish a Tribunal consisting of a Presiding Officer and two other`
  line `Members to decide such dispute and the decision of such Tribunal shall be final.`
  line `( 2 ) A person shall not be qualified for appointment, —`
  line `( a ) as a Presiding Officer of the Tribunal unless he has been a member of the Indian Legal`
  line `Service and has held a post in Grade I of the service for at least three years;`
  line `( b ) as a Member unless he has been a member of the Council for at least one full term and who is`
  line `not a sitting Member of the Council or who has not been a candidate in the election under dispute;`
  line and
  line `( c ) as a Member unless he holds the post of a Joint Secretary to the Government of India or any`
  line `other post under the Central Government carrying a scale of pay which is not less than that of a Joint`
  line `Secretary to the Government of India.`
  line `( 3 ) The terms and conditions of service of the Presiding Officer and Members of the Tribunal, their`
  line `place of meetings, remuneration and allowances shall be such as may be prescribed.`
  line `( 4 ) The expenses of the Tribunal shall be borne by the Council.`
  line `17. President, Vice-President and Honorary Secretary. — ( 1 ) The Council shall, at its first meeting,`
  line `elect three of its members from amongst persons referred to in clause ( a ) of sub-section ( 2 ) of section 12,`
  line `to be respectively the President, Vice-President and Honorary Secretary thereof, and as often as the office`
  line `of the President, Vice-President and Honorary Secretary falls vacant, the Council shall choose one of the`
  line `member in the same manner:`
  line `Provided that the Chairperson of the Council of the Actuarial Society shall continue to hold such`
  line `office as President after the commencement of this Act, until such time as a President is elected under the`
  line `provisions of this sub-section.`
  line `( 2 ) The President shall be the Chief Executive Officer of the Council.`
  line `( 3 ) The President, the Vice-President or the Honorary Secretary shall hold office for a period of two`
  line `years from the date on which he is chosen provided that he continues to be a member of the Council.`
  line `( 4 ) The President and the Vice-President shall, notwithstanding the expiration of his term, continue to`
  line `hold office until his successor enters upon his office.`
  line `( 5 ) In the event of occurrence of any vacancy in the office of the President, the Vice-President shall`
  line `act as the President until a new President is elected in accordance with the provisions of this section to fill`
  line `such vacancy and enters upon his office.`
  line `( 6 ) When the President is unable to discharge his functions owing to absence, illness or any other`
  line `cause, the Vice-President shall discharge his functions until the President resumes his duties.`
  line `18. Resignation from membership and filling up of casual vacancies. — ( 1 ) Any member of the`
  line `Council may at any time resign his membership by writing under his hand addressed to the President, and`
  line `the seat of such member shall become vacant when such resignation is accepted and notified by the`
  line Council.
obj_root_law_sections_9_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_10:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-10
  sectionNo (10)
  orderNo 10
  title `Page 10`
  content obj_root_law_sections_10_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_10_footnotes
  sourcePage 10
obj_root_law_sections_10_content:
  string
  line 10
  line `( 2 ) A member of the Council, other than a member nominated under clause ( b ) of sub-section ( 2 ) of`
  line `section 12 shall be deemed to have vacated his seat if he is declared by the Council to have been absent`
  line `without sufficient reason from three consecutive meetings of the Council, or of any of the Committees`
  line `constituted by the Council, and of which he is a member or he has been found guilty of any professional`
  line `or other misconduct and awarded penalty of fine or if his name is, for any cause, removed from the`
  line `register under the provisions of sections 24 and 30.`
  line `( 3 ) A casual vacancy in the office of a member of the Council shall be filled by fresh election or by`
  line `nomination by the Central Government, as the case may be, and the person elected or nominated to fill the`
  line `vacancy shall hold office only for the remainder of the term for which the member in whose place he was`
  line `elected or nominated would have held that office:`
  line `Provided that no election shall be held to fill a casual vacancy occurring within one year prior to the`
  line `date of the expiration of the term of such member.`
  line `( 4 ) No act done by the Council shall be called in question on the ground merely of the existence of`
  line `any vacancy in, or defect in the constitution of the Council.`
  line `19. Functions of Council. — ( 1 ) The duty of carrying out the functions under the provisions of this`
  line `Act shall be vested in the Council.`
  line `( 2 ) In particular and without prejudice to the generality of the foregoing power, the functions of the`
  line `Council shall include —`
  line `( a ) the holding of examination of the candidates for enrolment and specifying fees therefor;`
  line `( b ) the specifying of qualifications for entry in the register;`
  line `( c ) the recognition of foreign qualifications and training for the purposes of enrolment;`
  line `( d ) the granting of or refusal to grant the certificate of practice under this Act;`
  line `( e ) the maintenance and publication of a register of persons qualified to practice as Actuaries;`
  line `( f ) the levy and collection of fees from members, students, examinees and other persons;`
  line `( g ) the removal of names from the register and the restoration to the register of names which have`
  line `been removed;`
  line `( h ) the regulation and maintenance of the status and standard of professional qualifications of`
  line `members of the Institute;`
  line `( i ) to issue guidelines for the observance of the members, including the student members;`
  line `( j ) to receive gifts, grants, donations or benefactions from the Central or State Governments and`
  line `to receive bequests, donations and transfer of movable or immovable properties from testators, donors`
  line `or transferors, as the case may be;`
  line `( k ) co-operating with educational or other institutions in any part of the world having objects`
  line `wholly or partly similar to those of the Institute by exchange of members and generally in such`
  line `manner as may be conducive to achievement of their common objects;`
  line `( l ) instituting and awarding fellowships, scholarships, prizes and medals;`
  line `( m ) giving gifts, grants, donations or benefactions to other institutions or bodies having objects`
  line `similar to those of the Institute;`
  line `( n ) the carrying out, by granting financial assistance to persons other than members of the`
  line `Council, or in any other manner, of research in the actuarial science;`
  line `( o ) the maintenance of a library and publication of books, journals and periodicals relating to`
  line `actuarial science;`
  line `( p ) the exercise of disciplinary powers conferred by this Act;`
obj_root_law_sections_10_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_11:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-11
  sectionNo (11)
  orderNo 11
  title `Page 11`
  content obj_root_law_sections_11_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_11_footnotes
  sourcePage 11
obj_root_law_sections_11_content:
  string
  line 11
  line `( q ) establishing such regional council or councils as may be decided from time to time and fixing`
  line `their headquarters; and`
  line `( r ) doing all such things as may be necessary, incidental or conducive to the attainment of all or`
  line `any of the objects of the Institute.`
  line `20. Staff, remuneration and allowances. — ( 1 ) For the efficient performance of its functions, the`
  line `Council may —`
  line `( a ) appoint an Executive Director, a Treasurer and such other officers and employees as it deems`
  line `necessary and fix their salaries, fees, allowances and other conditions of service; and`
  line `( b ) fix the allowances of the President, the Vice-President, the Honorary Secretary and other`
  line `members of the Council and its Committees, in such manner as may be specified.`
  line `( 2 ) The Executive Director of the Council shall be entitled to participate in the meetings of the`
  line `Council but shall not be entitled to vote thereat.`
  line `21. Committees of Council. — ( 1 ) The Council may constitute such committees from amongst its`
  line `members, and co-opt therein persons who are not members of the Institute, as it deems necessary for the`
  line `purpose of carrying out the provisions of this Act:`
  line `Provided that the number of co-opted members shall not exceed one-third of the total membership of`
  line `the committee.`
  line `( 2 ) Every committee constituted under this section shall elect its own Chairman:`
  line `Provided that —`
  line `( i ) where the President is a member of such committee, he shall be the Chairman of such`
  line `committee, and in his absence, the Vice-President, if he is a member of such committee, shall be its`
  line `Chairman; and`
  line `( ii ) where the President is not a member of such committee but the Vice-President is a member,`
  line `he shall be its Chairman.`
  line `( 3 ) The committees shall exercise such functions and be subject to such conditions as may be`
  line specified.
  line `22. Finances of Council. — ( 1 ) There shall be established a fund under the management and control`
  line `of the Council into which shall be paid all moneys (including donations and grants) received by the`
  line `Council and out of which shall be met all expenses and liabilities incurred by the Council.`
  line `( 2 ) The Council may invest any money for the time being standing to the credit of the fund in any`
  line `security as it may deem prudent consistent with the considerations of security of such investments and`
  line `maximum returns thereon.`
  line `Explanation. — For the purposes of this sub-section, the expression "securities" shall have the`
  line `meaning assigned to it in section 2 of the Securities Contracts (Regulation) Act, 1956 (42 of 1956) as`
  line `amended from time to time.`
  line `( 3 ) The Council shall keep proper accounts of the fund distinguishing capital account from revenue`
  line account.
  line `( 4 ) The annual accounts of the Institute shall be subject to audit by a Chartered Accountant in practice`
  line `within the meaning of the Chartered Accountants Act, 1949 (38 of 1949) to be appointed annually by the`
  line `Council:`
  line `Provided that no member of the Council who is a Chartered Accountant or a person who is in`
  line `partnership with such member shall be eligible for appointment as an auditor under this sub-section.`
  line `( 5 ) As soon as may be practicable at the end of each year, but not later than the 30th day of`
  line `September of the year next following, the Council shall cause to be published in the Gazette of India, a`
  line `copy of the audited accounts and the report of the Council for that year and copies of the said accounts`
  line `and report shall be forwarded to the Central Government and to all the members of the Institute.`
obj_root_law_sections_11_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_12:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-12
  sectionNo (12)
  orderNo 12
  title `Page 12`
  content obj_root_law_sections_12_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_12_footnotes
  sourcePage 12
obj_root_law_sections_12_content:
  string
  line 12
  line `( 6 ) The Council may borrow from a scheduled bank, as defined in the Reserve Bank of India Act,`
  line `1934 (2 of 1934) or from any public financial institution —`
  line `( a ) any money required for meeting its liabilities on capital account on the security of the fund or`
  line `on the security of any other asset, for the time being belonging to it; or`
  line `( b ) for the purpose of meeting current liabilities, pending the receipt of income, by way of`
  line `temporary loan or overdraft.`
  line `Explanation. — The expression "public financial institution" means a financial institution specified in`
  line `section 4A of the Companies Act, 1956 (1 of 1956).`
  line `CHAPTER III`
  line `R EGISTER OF MEMBERS`
  line `23. Register. — ( 1 ) The Council shall maintain in the specified manner a register of the members of`
  line `the Institute.`
  line `( 2 ) The register shall include the following particulars about every member of the Institute, namely: —`
  line `( a ) his full name, date of birth, domicile, residential and professional addresses;`
  line `( b ) the date on which his name is entered in the register;`
  line `( c ) his qualifications;`
  line `( d ) whether he holds a certificate of practice; and`
  line `( e ) any other particulars which may be specified.`
  line `( 3 ) The Council shall cause to be published in such manner as may be specified a list of members as`
  line `on the 1st day of April each year, and shall, if requested to do so by any such member, send him a copy of`
  line `such list, on payment of such amount as may be specified.`
  line `( 4 ) Every member of the Institute shall, on his name being entered in the register, pay such annual`
  line `membership fee as may be specified by the Council.`
  line `24. Removal of name from Register. — The Council may, by order, remove from the register the`
  line `name of any member of the Institute —`
  line `( a ) who is dead; or`
  line `( b ) from whom a request has been received to that effect; or`
  line `( c ) who has not paid any specified fee required to be paid by him; or`
  line `( d ) who is found to have been subject to, at the time when his name was entered in the register, or`
  line `who at any time thereafter has become subject to, any of the disqualifications mentioned in section`
  line `11; or`
  line `( e ) who for any other reason has ceased to be entitled to have his name borne on the register.`
  line `25. Re-entry in register. — The Council may re-enter the name of a member whose name has been`
  line `removed from the register for reasons mentioned in clauses ( b ), ( c ), ( d ) and ( e ) of section 24, by an order,`
  line `and on paying such fees, and after satisfying such conditions and requirements as may be specified.`
obj_root_law_sections_12_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_13:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-13
  sectionNo (13)
  orderNo 13
  title `Page 13`
  content obj_root_law_sections_13_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_13_footnotes
  sourcePage 13
obj_root_law_sections_13_content:
  string
  line 13
  line `CHAPTER IV`
  line `M ISCONDUCT`
  line `26. Disciplinary Committee. — ( 1 ) The Council shall constitute a Disciplinary Committee consisting`
  line `of the President or the Vice-President of the Council as the Presiding Officer and two members of the`
  line `Council elected by the Council and two members to be nominated by the Central Government from`
  line `amongst the persons of eminence having experience in the field of law, education, economics, business,`
  line `finance, accountancy or public administration:`
  line `Provided that the Council may constitute more regional Disciplinary Committees as and when it`
  line `deems fit.`
  line `( 2 ) The Disciplinary Committee in making the inquiry under the provisions of this Act shall follow`
  line `such procedure and submit the report to the Council within such time as may be prescribed.`
  line `27. Appointment of Prosecution Director. — ( 1 ) The Council may, by notification, appoint a`
  line `Prosecution Director and such other employees to assist the Disciplinary Committee in making inquiries`
  line `in respect of any information or complaint received by the Council under the provisions of this Act.`
  line `( 2 ) In order to make inquiries under the provisions of this Act, the Prosecution Director shall follow`
  line `such procedure as may be prescribed.`
  line `28. Authority, Council, Disciplinary Committee and Prosecution Director to have powers of`
  line `civil court. — For the purposes of an inquiry under the provisions of this Act, the Authority, the`
  line `Disciplinary Committee and the Prosecution Director shall have the same powers as are vested in a civil`
  line `court under the Code of Civil Procedure, 1908 (5 of 1908), in respect of the following matters, namely: —`
  line `( a ) summoning and enforcing the attendance of any person and examining him on oath;`
  line `( b ) the discovery and production of any document; and`
  line `( c ) receiving evidence on affidavit.`
  line `29. Action by Council on Disciplinary Committee's report. — ( 1 ) On receipt of a report from the`
  line `Disciplinary Committee, if the Council is satisfied that the member of the Institute is guilty of any`
  line `professional or other misconduct, it shall record its findings accordingly and shall proceed in accordance`
  line `with the provisions of section 30.`
  line `( 2 ) In case the Council is not satisfied with the report of the Disciplinary Committee and is of the`
  line `opinion that it requires further inquiry, it may refer the report again to the Disciplinary Committee for`
  line `such further inquiry as may be directed through an order of the Council.`
  line `( 3 ) If the Council disagrees with the findings of the Disciplinary Committee, it may direct the`
  line `Prosecution Director or itself make an appeal to the Authority.`
  line `30. Member to be afforded opportunity of being heard. — Where the Council is of the opinion that`
  line `a member is guilty of a professional or other misconduct mentioned in the Schedule, it shall afford to the`
  line `member a reasonable opportunity of being heard before making any order against him and may thereafter`
  line `take any one or more of the following actions, namely: —`
  line `( a ) reprimand the member; or`
  line `( b ) remove the name of the member from the register permanently or for such period, as it thinks`
  line fit.
  line `( c ) impose such fine as it may think fit, which may extend to five lakh rupees.`
  line `Explanation. — For the purposes of this section, “member of the Institute” includes a person who was`
  line `a member of the Institute on the date of the alleged misconduct although he has ceased to be a member of`
  line `the Institute at the time of the inquiry.`
  line `31. Professional or other misconduct defined. — For the purposes of this Act, the expression`
  line `“ professional or other misconduct ” shall be deemed to include any act or omission provided in the`
  line `Schedule, but nothing in this section shall be construed to limit or abridge in any way the power conferred`
obj_root_law_sections_13_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_14:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-14
  sectionNo (14)
  orderNo 14
  title `Page 14`
  content obj_root_law_sections_14_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_14_footnotes
  sourcePage 14
obj_root_law_sections_14_content:
  string
  line 14
  line `or duty cast on the Disciplinary Committee or the Prosecution Director to inquire into the conduct of any`
  line `member of the Institute under any other circumstances.`
  line `CHAPTER V`
  line `A PPEALS`
  line `32. Constitution of Appellate Authority. — The Appellate Authority constituted under sub-section`
  line `( 1 ) of section 22A of the Chartered Accountants Act, 1949 (38 of 1949), shall be deemed to be the`
  line `Appellate Authority for the purposes of this Act subject to the modification that for clause ( b ) of said sub-`
  line `section ( 1 ), the following clause had been substituted, namely: —`
  line `“ ( b ) the Central Government shall, by notification, appoint two part-time Members from amongst`
  line `the persons who have been members of the Council of the Institute of Actuaries for at least one full`
  line `term and who are not sitting members of the Council;”.`
  line `33. Term of office of Members of Authority. — A person appointed as a Member shall hold office`
  line `for a term of three years from the date on which he enters upon his office or until he attains the age of`
  line `sixty-seven years, whichever is earlier.`
  line `34. Allowances, conditions of service of Members and procedure, etc., of Authority. — The`
  line `provisions of section 22C, section 22D and section 22F of the Chartered Accountants Act, 1949 (38 of`
  line `1949) shall apply to the Authority in relation to allowances and terms and conditions of service of its`
  line `Chairperson and members, and in discharge of its functions under this Act as they apply to it in the`
  line `discharge of its functions under the Chartered Accountants Act, 1949.`
  line `35. Officers and other staff of Authority. — ( 1 ) The Council shall make available to the Authority`
  line `such officers and other staff members as may be necessary for the efficient performance of the functions`
  line `of the Authority.`
  line `( 2 ) The salaries and allowances and conditions of service of the officers and other staff members of`
  line `the Authority shall be such as may be specified.`
  line `36. Appeal to Authority. — ( 1 ) Any member of the Institute aggrieved by any order of the Council`
  line `imposing on him any of the penalties referred to in section 30, may, within ninety days of the date on`
  line `which the order is communicated to him, prefer an appeal to the Authority:`
  line `Provided that the Authority may entertain any such appeal after the expiry of the said period of ninety`
  line `days, if it is satisfied that there was sufficient cause for not filing the appeal in time.`
  line `( 2 ) The Authority may, after calling for the records of any case, revise any order made by the Council`
  line `under section 30 and may —`
  line `( a ) confirm, modify or set aside the order;`
  line `( b ) impose any penalty or set aside, reduce or enhance the penalty imposed by the order;`
  line `( c ) remit the case to the Disciplinary Committee for such further inquiry as the Authority`
  line `considers proper in the circumstances of the case; or`
  line `( d ) pass such other order as the Authority thinks fit:`
  line `Provided that the Authority shall give an opportunity of being heard to the parties concerned before`
  line `passing any order.`
  line `CHAPTER VI`
  line `P ENALTIES`
  line `37. Penalty for falsely claiming to be a member, etc. — Subject to the provisions of section 10, any`
  line `person who, —`
  line `( a ) not being a member of the Institute, —`
  line `( i ) represents that he is a member of the Institute in any of the manners mentioned in section`
  line `7; or`
obj_root_law_sections_14_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_15:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-15
  sectionNo (15)
  orderNo 15
  title `Page 15`
  content obj_root_law_sections_15_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_15_footnotes
  sourcePage 15
obj_root_law_sections_15_content:
  string
  line 15
  line `( ii ) uses the designation "Actuary"; or`
  line `( iii ) uses the letters "AIAI" or "FIAI" after his name; or`
  line `( iv ) practises the profession of an Actuary; or`
  line `( b ) being a member of the Institute, but not having a certificate of practice, represents that he is in`
  line `practice, or practises as an Actuary,`
  line `shall be punishable on first conviction with fine which may extend to one lakh rupees, and on any`
  line `subsequent conviction with imprisonment which may extend to one year, or with fine which may extend`
  line `to two lakh rupees, or with both.`
  line `38. Penalty for using name of Institution, awarding degrees of actuarial science, etc. — ( 1 ) Save`
  line `as otherwise provided in this Act, no person shall —`
  line `( a ) use a name or a common seal which is identical with the name or the common seal of the`
  line `Institute or so nearly resembles it so as to deceive or as is likely to deceive the public; or`
  line `( b ) award any degree, diploma or certificate or bestow any designation which indicates or`
  line `purports to indicate the position or attainment of any qualification or competence in actuaryship`
  line `similar to that of a member of the Institute; or`
  line `( c ) seek to regulate in any manner whatsoever the profession of Actuaries.`
  line `( 2 ) Any person contravening the provisions of sub-section ( 1 ) shall, without prejudice to any other`
  line `proceedings, which may be taken against him, be punishable with fine, which may extend on first`
  line `conviction to fifty thousand rupees and on any subsequent conviction with imprisonment which may`
  line `extend to one year, or, with fine which may extend to one lakh rupees, or with both.`
  line `( 3 ) Nothing contained in this section shall apply to any University or other institution established by`
  line `law or to any body affiliated to the Institute.`
  line `39. Companies not to engage in actuarial practice. — ( 1 ) No company, whether incorporated in`
  line `India or elsewhere, shall practice as Actuaries.`
  line `( 2 ) Any company contravening the provisions of sub-section ( 1 ) shall be punishable on first`
  line `conviction with fine which may extend to ten thousand rupees, and on any subsequent conviction with`
  line `fine which may extend to twenty-five thousand rupees.`
  line `40. Unqualified person not to sign documents. — ( 1 ) No person other than a fellow member of the`
  line `Institute shall sign any document on behalf of an Actuary in practice or a firm of such Actuaries in his or`
  line `its professional capacity.`
  line `( 2 ) Any person contravening the provisions of sub-section ( 1 ) shall, without prejudice to any other`
  line `proceedings which may be taken against him, be punishable on first conviction with fine which may`
  line `extend to fifty thousand rupees, and on any subsequent conviction with imprisonment which may extend`
  line `to one year, or with fine which may extend to one lakh rupees, or with both.`
  line `41. Offences by companies. — ( 1 ) If the person committing an offence under this Act is a company,`
  line `the company as well as every person in charge of, and responsible to, the company for the conduct of its`
  line `business at the time of the commission of the offence shall be deemed to be guilty of the offence and shall`
  line `be liable to be proceeded against and punished accordingly:`
  line `Provided that nothing contained in this sub-section shall render any such person liable to any`
  line `punishment if he proves that the offence was committed without his knowledge or that he had exercised`
  line `all due diligence to prevent the commission of such offence.`
obj_root_law_sections_15_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_16:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-16
  sectionNo (16)
  orderNo 16
  title `Page 16`
  content obj_root_law_sections_16_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_16_footnotes
  sourcePage 16
obj_root_law_sections_16_content:
  string
  line 16
  line `( 2 ) Notwithstanding anything contained in sub-section ( 1 ), where an offence under this Act has been`
  line `committed by a company and it is proved that the offence has been committed with the consent or`
  line `connivance of, or that the commission of the offence is attributable to any neglect on the part of, any`
  line `director, manager, secretary or other officer of the company, such director, manager, secretary or other`
  line `officer shall also be deemed to be guilty of that offence and shall be liable to be proceeded against and`
  line `punished accordingly.`
  line `Explanation. — For the purposes of this section —`
  line `( a ) "company" means any body corporate and includes a firm or other association of individuals;`
  line and
  line `( b ) "director", in relation to a firm, means a partner in the firm.`
  line `42. Sanction to prosecute. — No person shall be prosecuted under this Act except on a complaint`
  line `made by or under the order of the Council or of the Central Government.`
  line `CHAPTER VII`
  line `Q UALITY R EVIEW B OARD`
  line `43. Establishment of Quality Review Board. — ( 1 ) The Central Government shall, by notification,`
  line `constitute a Quality Review Board consisting of a Chairperson and not more than four Members:`
  line `Provided that in case the Board is constituted with two Members, one each shall be nominated by the`
  line `Council and the Central Government, respectively.`
  line `( 2 ) The Chairperson and Members of the Board shall be appointed from amongst the persons of`
  line `eminence having experience in the field of law, education, economics, business, finance, accountancy or`
  line `public administration.`
  line `( 3 ) Two Members of the Board shall be nominated by the Council and other two Members shall be`
  line `nominated by the Central Government.`
  line `44. Functions of Board. — The Board shall perform the following functions, namely: —`
  line `( a ) to fix standards for the services provided by the members of the Institute;`
  line `( b ) to review the quality of services provided by the members of the Institute including actuarial`
  line `audit services; and`
  line `( c ) to guide the members of the Institute to improve the quality of services and adherence to the`
  line `various statutory and other regulatory requirements.`
  line `45. Procedure of Board. — The Board shall follow in its meeting and in discharging its functions`
  line `such procedure as may be prescribed.`
  line `46. Terms and conditions of Chairperson and Members of Board. — The terms and conditions of`
  line `service of the Chairperson and the Members of the Board, their place of meetings, remuneration and`
  line `allowances shall be such as may be prescribed.`
  line `47. Expenditure of Board. — The expenditure of the Board shall be borne by the Council.`
  line `CHAPTER VIII`
  line `D ISSOLUTION OF THE A CTUARIAL S OCIETY OF I NDIA R EGISTERED UNDER THE S OCIETIES`
  line `R EGISTRATION A CT`
  line `48. Dissolution of Actuarial Society of India. — On the appointed day, —`
  line `( a ) the Society known as the Actuarial Society of India registered under the Societies Registration`
  line `Act, 1860 (21 of 1860) and the Bombay Public Trusts Act, 1950 (Bombay Act XXXIX of 1950) shall`
  line `stand dissolved and thereafter no person shall make, assert or take any claims or demands or`
  line `proceedings against the dissolved society or against any officer thereof in his capacity as such officer`
  line `except in so far as may be necessary, for enforcing the provisions of this Act;`
obj_root_law_sections_16_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_17:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-17
  sectionNo (17)
  orderNo 17
  title `Page 17`
  content obj_root_law_sections_17_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_17_footnotes
  sourcePage 17
obj_root_law_sections_17_content:
  string
  line 17
  line `( b ) the right of every member to, or in respect of, the dissolved society shall be extinguished, and`
  line `thereafter no member of the society shall make, assert or take any claims or demands or proceedings in`
  line `respect of that society except as provided in this Act.`
  line `49. Provisions respecting employees of dissolved society. — ( 1 ) Every person employed in the`
  line `dissolved society and continuing in its employment immediately before the commencement of this Act`
  line `shall, as from such commencement, become an employee of the Institute, shall hold his office or service`
  line `therein by the same tenure and upon the same terms and conditions and with the same rights and`
  line `privileges as to retirement benefits as he would have held the same under the dissolved society if this Act`
  line `had not been passed, and shall, continue to do so unless and until his employment in the Institute is`
  line `terminated or until his remuneration, terms and conditions of employment are duly altered by the`
  line Institute.
  line `( 2 ) Notwithstanding anything contained in the Industrial Disputes Act, 1947 (14 of 1947) or in any`
  line `other law for the time being in force, the transfer of the services of any employee of the dissolved society`
  line `to the Institute shall not entitle any such employee to any compensation under that Act or other law, and`
  line `no such claims shall be entertained by any court, tribunal or other authority.`
  line `CHAPTER IX`
  line `M ISCELLANEOUS`
  line `50. Maintenance of more than one offices by Actuary. — ( 1 ) Where an Actuary in practice or a firm`
  line `of such Actuaries has more than one offices within or outside India, each one of such offices shall be in`
  line `the separate charge of a fellow member of the Institute:`
  line `Provided that the Council may in suitable cases exempt any Actuary in practice or firm of such`
  line `Actuaries from the operation of this sub-section.`
  line `( 2 ) Every Actuary in practice or a firm of such Actuaries maintaining more than one office shall send`
  line `to the Council a list of offices and the person in charge thereof and shall keep the Council informed of any`
  line `changes in relation thereto.`
  line `51. Reciprocity. — ( 1 ) Where any country, notified by the Central Government in this behalf in the`
  line `Official Gazette, prevents persons of Indian domicile from becoming members of any institution similar`
  line `to the Institute or from practicing the profession of Actuaries or subjects them to unfair discrimination in`
  line `that country, no subject of any such country shall be entitled to become a member of the Institute or`
  line `practice the profession of Actuaries in India.`
  line `( 2 ) Subject to the provisions of sub-section ( 1 ), the Council may specify the conditions, if any, subject`
  line `to which foreign qualifications relating to actuarial science shall be recognised for the purposes of entry in`
  line `the register.`
  line `52. Power of Central Government to issue directions. — ( 1 ) For the purposes of this Act, the`
  line `Central Government may, from time to time, give to the Council such general or special directions as it`
  line `thinks fit, and the Council shall, in the discharge of its functions under this Act, comply with such`
  line directions.
  line `( 2 ) If, in the opinion of the Central Government, the Council has persistently made default in giving`
  line `effect to the directions issued under sub-section ( 1 ), it may, after giving an opportunity of being heard to`
  line `the Council, by notification, dissolve the Council, whereafter a new Council shall be constituted in`
  line `accordance with the provisions of this Act with effect from such date as may be decided by the Central`
  line Government.
  line `( 3 ) Where the Central Government has issued a notification under sub-section ( 2 ) dissolving the`
  line `Council, it may, pending the constitution of a new Council in accordance with the provisions of this Act,`
  line `authorise any person or body of persons to take over the management of the affairs of the Council and to`
  line `exercise such functions as may be mentioned in the notification.`
  line `53. Protection of action taken in good faith. — No suit, prosecution or other legal proceeding shall`
  line `lie against the Central Government or the Council or the Disciplinary Committee or the Tribunal or the`
  line `Authority or the Board or the Prosecution Director or any officer of that Government, Council,`
obj_root_law_sections_17_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_18:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-18
  sectionNo (18)
  orderNo 18
  title `Page 18`
  content obj_root_law_sections_18_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_18_footnotes
  sourcePage 18
obj_root_law_sections_18_content:
  string
  line 18
  line `Committee, Tribunal, Authority or Board, for anything which is in good faith done or intended to be done`
  line `under this Act or any rule, regulation, notification, direction or order made thereunder.`
  line `54. Members, etc., to be public servants. — The Chairperson, Presiding Officer, Members and other`
  line `officers and employees of the Authority, Tribunal and Board, and the Prosecution Director shall be`
  line `deemed to be public servants within the meaning of section 21 of the Indian Penal Code (45 of 1860).`
  line `55. Power of Central Government to make rules. — ( 1 ) The Central Government may, by`
  line `notification, make rules to carry out the provisions of this Act.`
  line `( 2 ) In particular and without prejudice to the generality of the foregoing power, such rules may`
  line `provide for all or any of the following matters, namely: —`
  line `( a ) the manner of election and nomination in respect of members to the Council under sub-section`
  line `( 2 ) of section 12;`
  line `( b ) the terms and conditions of service of the Presiding Officers and Members of the Tribunal,`
  line `place of meeting, remuneration and allowances to be paid to them under sub-section ( 3 ) of section 16;`
  line `( c ) the procedure of inquiry and submission of report by the Disciplinary Committee under sub-`
  line `section ( 2 ) of section 26;`
  line `( d ) the procedure of inquiry by the Prosecution Director under sub-section ( 2 ) of section 27;`
  line `( e ) any act or omission which may be determined as professional misconduct under section 31;`
  line `( f ) the procedure to be followed by the Board in its meetings and discharging its functions under`
  line `section 45; and`
  line `( g ) terms and conditions of service of the Chairman and Members of the Board under section 46.`
  line `56. Power to make regulations. — ( 1 ) The Council may, with the previous approval of the Central`
  line `Government and subject to the previous publication, by notification in the Official Gazette, make`
  line `regulations to carry out the provisions of this Act.`
  line `( 2 ) In particular, and without prejudice to the generality of the foregoing power, such regulations may`
  line `provide for all or any of the following matters, namely: —`
  line `( a ) the examination and training for the purposes of clauses ( b ), ( c ) and ( d ) of sub-section ( 1 ) of`
  line `section 6;`
  line `( b ) the manner of making an application under sub-section ( 3 ) of section 6;`
  line `( c ) the fees payable under sub-section ( 3 ) of section 6, sub-section ( 2 ) of section 9, clause ( a ) of`
  line `sub-section ( 2 ) of section 19, sub-section ( 4 ) of section 23;`
  line `( d ) the manner in which the honorary member may be chosen under sub-section ( 1 ) of section 8;`
  line `( e ) the terms and conditions on which an affiliate member may be admitted under sub-section ( 2 )`
  line `of section 8;`
  line `( f ) the academic qualifications for admission of a student member under sub-section ( 3 ) of section`
  line 8;
  line `( g ) qualifications required for a certificate of practice under sub-section ( 1 ) and the form in which`
  line `an application may be made under sub-section ( 2 ) of section 9;`
  line `( h ) the transaction of business by the Council for the discharge of its functions mentioned in sub-`
  line `section ( 2 ) of section 19;`
  line `( i ) terms and conditions of the services under sub-section ( 1 ) of section 20;`
  line `( j ) the functions and conditions of the committees under sub-section ( 3 ) of section 21;`
  line `( k ) the manner in which the register of the members of the Institute and other particulars to be`
  line `maintained under sub-sections ( 1 ) and ( 2 ) of section 23;`
obj_root_law_sections_18_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_19:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-19
  sectionNo (19)
  orderNo 19
  title `Page 19`
  content obj_root_law_sections_19_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_19_footnotes
  sourcePage 19
obj_root_law_sections_19_content:
  string
  line 19
  line `( l ) the manner in which the annual list of members of the Institute may be published under sub-`
  line `section ( 3 ) of section 23;`
  line `( m ) the conditions and requirements and payment of fee for re-entry in the register under section`
  line 25;
  line `( n ) salaries and allowances and conditions of service of the officers and other staff members of`
  line `the Authority under sub-section ( 2 ) of section 35;`
  line `( o ) the conditions subject to which foreign qualifications may be recognised under sub-section ( 2 )`
  line `of section 51; and`
  line `( p ) any other matter which is required to be, or may be, prescribed under this Act.`
  line `57. Power of Central Government to issue directions for making or amending regulations. — ( 1 )`
  line `Where the Central Government considers it expedient so to do, it may, by order in writing, direct the`
  line `Council to make any regulations or to amend or revoke any regulations already made within such period`
  line `as it may specify in this behalf.`
  line `( 2 ) If the Council fails or neglects to comply with such order within the specified period, the Central`
  line `Government may itself make the regulations or amend or revoke the regulations made by the Council.`
  line `58. Laying of rules and regulations. — Every rule and every regulation made under this Act shall be`
  line `laid, as soon as may be after it is made, before each House of Parliament, while it is in session, for a total`
  line `period of thirty days which may be comprised in one session or in two or more successive sessions, and`
  line `if, before the expiry of the session immediately following the session or the successive sessions aforesaid,`
  line `both Houses agree in making any modification in the rule or regulation or both Houses agree that the rule`
  line `or regulation should not be made, the rule or regulation shall, thereafter have effect only in such modified`
  line `form or be of no effect, as the case may be; so, however, that any such modification or annulment shall be`
  line `without prejudice to the validity of anything previously done under that rule or regulation.`
  line `59. Power to remove difficulties. — ( 1 ) If any difficulty arises in giving effect to the provisions of`
  line `this Act, the Central Government may, by order, published in the Official Gazette, make such provisions`
  line `not inconsistent with the provisions of this Act, as may appear to be necessary for removing the difficulty:`
  line `Provided that no such order shall be made under this section after the expiry of a period of two years`
  line `from the commencement of this Act.`
  line `( 2 ) Every order made under this section shall be laid, as soon as may be after it is made, before each`
  line `House of Parliament.`
obj_root_law_sections_19_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_20:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-20
  sectionNo (20)
  orderNo 20
  title `Page 20`
  content obj_root_law_sections_20_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_20_footnotes
  sourcePage 20
obj_root_law_sections_20_content:
  string
  line 20
  line `THE SCHEDULE`
  line `( See section 31)`
  line `P ART I`
  line `Professional misconduct in relation to members of the Institute in practice`
  line `An Actuary in practice shall be deemed to be guilty of professional misconduct, if he —`
  line `( 1 ) allows any person to practice in his name as an actuary unless such person is also an actuary`
  line `in practice and is in partnership with or employed by himself; or`
  line `( 2 ) pays by way of remuneration to an employee, pays or allows or agrees to pay or allow,`
  line `directly or indirectly, any share, commission or brokerage in the fees or profits of his professional`
  line `business, to any person other than a member of the Institute or a partner or a retired partner or the`
  line `legal representative of a deceased partner; or`
  line `( 3 ) enters into partnership with any person other than an Actuary in practice or a person resident`
  line `outside India who but for his residence abroad would be entitled to be admitted as a member under`
  line `clause ( c ) of sub-section ( 1 ) of section 6 or whose qualifications are recognised by the Central`
  line `Government or the Council for the purpose of permitting such partnership, provided the Actuary`
  line `shares in the fees or profits of the business of the partnership both within and outside of India; or`
  line `( 4 ) secures either through the services of a person who is not an employee of such Actuary or`
  line `who is not qualified to be his partner or by means which are not open to an Actuary, any professional`
  line `business; or`
  line `( 5 ) accepts an assignment as Actuary previously held by another Actuary without first`
  line `communicating with him in writing; or`
  line `( 6 ) charges or offers to charge, accepts or offers to accept in respect of any professional`
  line `employment fees which are based on a percentage of profit or which are contingent upon the findings`
  line `or results of such employment, except as permitted under any regulation made under this Act; or`
  line `( 7 ) engages in any business or occupation other than the profession of Actuaries unless permitted`
  line `by the Council so to engage:`
  line `Provided that nothing contained herein shall disentitle an Actuary from being a director of a`
  line `company; or`
  line `( 8 ) accepts a position as an actuary previously held by some other Actuary in practice in such`
  line `conditions as to constitute undercutting; or`
  line `( 9 ) allows a person not being a member of the Institute in practice, or a member not being his`
  line `partner to sign on his behalf or on behalf of his firm, any valuation report or financial statement; or`
  line `( 10 ) discloses information acquired in the course of his professional engagement to any person`
  line `other than his client so engaging him, without the consent of such client, or otherwise than as required`
  line `by any law for the time being in force; or`
  line `( 11 ) certifies or submits in his name, or in the name of his firm, a valuation report or a financial`
  line `statement unless the examination of such statement and the related records has been made by him or`
  line `by a partner or an employee in his firm or by another Actuary in practice; or`
  line `( 12 ) expresses his opinion or valuation reports or financial statements of any business or any`
  line `enterprise in which he, his firm, or a partner in his firm has a substantial interest, unless he has`
  line `disclosed the interest also in his report; or`
  line `( 13 ) fails to disclose a material fact known to him in a valuation report or a financial statement,`
  line `but disclosures of which is necessary to make the valuation report or the financial statement not`
  line `misleading where he is concerned with such valuation report or the financial statement in a`
  line `professional capacity; or`
obj_root_law_sections_20_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_21:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-21
  sectionNo (21)
  orderNo 21
  title `Page 21`
  content obj_root_law_sections_21_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_21_footnotes
  sourcePage 21
obj_root_law_sections_21_content:
  string
  line 21
  line `( 14 ) fails to report a material misstatement known to him to appear in a valuation report or`
  line `financial statement with which he is concerned in a professional capacity; or`
  line `( 15 ) is grossly negligent in the conduct of his professional duties; or`
  line `( 16 ) fails to obtain sufficient information to warrant the formation of an opinion in regard to any`
  line `matter contained in any valuation report or financial statement prepared by him or on his behalf; or`
  line `( 17 ) fails to invite attention to any material departure from the generally accepted procedure or`
  line `professional work applicable to the circumstances, in any valuation report or financial statement`
  line `prepared by him or on his behalf.`
  line `P ART II`
  line `Professional misconduct in relation to the members of the Institute in service`
  line `A member of the Institute (other than a member in practice) shall be deemed to be guilty of`
  line `professional misconduct, if he being an employee of any company, firm or person, —`
  line `( 1 ) pays or allows or agrees to pay directly or indirectly to any person any share in the`
  line `emoluments of the employment undertaken by him; or`
  line `( 2 ) accepts or agrees to accept any part of fees, profits or gains by way of commission or`
  line `gratification; or`
  line `( 3 ) discloses confidential information acquired in the course of his employment except as and`
  line `when required by law or except as permitted by his employer.`
  line `P ART III`
  line `Professional misconduct in relation to members of the Institute generally`
  line `A member of the Institute, whether in practice or not, shall be deemed to be guilty of professional`
  line `misconduct, if he —`
  line `( 1 ) includes in any statement, return or form to be submitted to the Council any particulars`
  line `knowing them to be false; or`
  line `( 2 ) not being a fellow member of the Institute acts himself as a fellow member of the Institute; or`
  line `( 3 ) does not supply the information called for or does not comply with the requirements asked for`
  line `by the Council or any of its Committees; or`
  line `( 4 ) contravenes any of the provisions of this Act or the regulations made thereunder or any`
  line `guidelines issued by the Council under clause ( i ) of sub-section ( 2 ) of section 19; or`
  line `( 5 ) is guilty of such other act or omission as may be specified by the Council.`
  line `P ART IV`
  line `Other misconduct in relation to member of the Institute generally`
  line `A member of the Institute, whether in practice or not, shall be deemed to be guilty of other`
  line `misconduct, if —`
  line `( A ) ( 1 ) he is held guilty by any civil or criminal court for an offence which is punishable with`
  line `imprisonment for a term not exceeding six months;`
  line `( 2 ) in the opinion of the Council, he brings disrepute to the profession or the Institute as result of`
  line `his action whether or not related to his professional work;`
  line `( B ) he is held guilty by any civil or criminal court for an offence which is punishable with`
  line `imprisonment for a term exceeding six months.`
obj_root_law_sections_21_footnotes:
  string
  line
